article.description: P.J. Tucker hit all nine of his shots, including his first career 3-pointer, to score 19 points in leading No. 2 Texas to a 90-55 win over Louisiana-Monroe.
article.headline: Tucker, Aldridge helps Longhorns cruise past La-Monroe
article.linkText: Tucker, Aldridge helps Longhorns cruise past La-Monroe
article.story:
AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- P.J. Tucker promised it was coming. He didn't put in all that work on his jump shot and scoring away from the basket not to try it sooner or later.

And now Texas' bullish forward is a long-range shooting threat.

Tucker hit all nine of his shots, including his first career 3-pointer, to score 19 points in leading No. 2 Texas to a 90-55 win over Louisiana-Monroe on Saturday.

"It didn't feel any different," Tucker said of his 3-pointer from the right corner in the second half, his first attempt from that range this season and only the second of his career. "It just counted for one extra point."

An undersized power forward the last two season, the muscular 6-foot-5 Tucker has moved to small forward this season. That meant making the transition to scoring away from the basket with pull-up jumpers to go with his tenacious work under the rim.

His only blemish on an otherwise perfect shooting night was a pair of missed free throws late in the second half.

"I think it's just being versatile," Tucker said. "They give me the ball where they know I'm effective. Doing it so much in practice, in games it comes natural."

After tough wins over No. 13 West Virginia and Iowa (No. 17 ESPN/USA Today, No. 18 AP), the Longhorns (5-0) coasted past the overmatched Indians. LaMarcus Aldridge had his fifth consecutive double-double with 21 points and 11 rebounds. Texas shot 50 percent from the floor and outrebounded Louisiana-Monroe 41-28.

Cecil Hood led Louisiana-Monroe (3-3) with 15 points.

The Longhorns played without starting forward Brad Buckman, who sat out the game with a hip injury. But even with him on the bench, the Longhorns were too physical up front and too quick in the backcourt. An early rash of turnovers and fouls by the Indians allowed Texas to seize control quickly.

Texas forced 14 turnovers in the first half. Tucker had four steals, the first leading to an Aldridge dunk. Aldridge then tipped the ball to A.J. Abrams for a 3-pointer and Tucker's second steal led to an easy layup.

Another dunk by Aldridge on a perfect feed from Daniel Gibson, followed by two more 3-pointers from Gibson and Connor Atchley in an 18-5 Texas run opened up a 37-17 lead and Texas pulled away from there.

"We've had a problem taking care of the ball all year long," Indians coach Orlando Early said. "It was also them. As the game went on, it was more them than us. They just physically dominated us."

If Texas struggled, it was from 3-point range, where the Longhorns were 8-of-26. Gibson, the Longhorns' best long-range shooter, hit 9-of-17 away from home against West Virginia and Iowa but has struggled to find the same stroke in Texas' three easy
wins. He was 2-of-9 against Louisiana-Monroe.

Texas coach Rick Barnes said he's not worried about Gibson's shooting.

"Daniel will be fine," Barnes said. "There's going to be nights you're not going to shoot the ball well. We still shot 50 percent for the game and scored 90 points."

The Longhorns' bigger concern might be Tucker taking to bragging about his soft touch.

The game was barely over when he started teasing Gibson about who had the better shooting night. His 3-pointer came with Texas leading 43-31 and sparked the second-half surge that kept the Indians from staging any kind of a rally.

"P.J. will make sure every knows about it," Barnes said.
